  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Open homes are the single most efficient way to get serious buyers through a property in a short window. They are also the only time during a campaign when you invite a stream of strangers into your home with minimal personal screening. The vast majority of those strangers are genuine inspectors. A small fraction are opportunistic about valuables, mail, or sensitive information. A smaller fraction again is using the open home as deliberate reconnaissance.</p>

      <p>The right way to think about open home security is as a manageable risk rather than a reason to avoid open homes. Tens of thousands of open homes happen across Brisbane every year. The incidents that occur are almost always opportunistic and almost always preventable with basic preparation. The framework below covers what is realistic to worry about, what is not, and how to set the campaign up so the risk is genuinely small.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The risk profile</h2>

      <p>Open homes invite strangers into your home. The vast majority are genuine inspectors who are there to look at the property because they are considering an offer or are interested in what is selling in the area. A meaningful portion of attendees are neighbours, friends of neighbours, or local residents curious about a property they have walked past for years. The remaining fraction is the one to think about: a small number of opportunistic visitors who use the open home as cover to take small portable items, or who note details about the home for a possible later visit.</p>

      <p>The risk is not zero. It is also not large. It is in the same broad category as the risk of having a tradesperson in your home for an afternoon: most are professional, a small fraction is opportunistic, and the way to manage it is preparation rather than avoidance.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What gets stolen at open homes</h2>

      <p>The pattern across reported incidents is consistent. The items that go missing are small, portable, and easy to leave with discreetly. In rough order of frequency:</p>

      <p>Small portable valuables: jewellery (particularly items left in bedside tables and bathroom vanities), watches, smaller electronics like AirPods and chargers, cash left in drawers or cupboards. These items can fit in a pocket and be carried out without raising any suspicion.</p>

      <p>Prescription medications from bathrooms: a smaller but persistent category. Bathroom cabinets are a routine inspection point because buyers want to assess storage and condition, and unsecured prescription medications are at risk during the few seconds an inspector is alone in that space.</p>

      <p>Personal documents: mail left in the entry, financial statements visible on the kitchen bench, ID copies on a study desk. These are sometimes taken for identity-theft purposes rather than for resale value, which makes them a higher-impact theft despite the items being free in a strict dollar sense.</p>

      <p>Computer credentials: passwords on sticky notes near a desk, unlocked devices that an inspector can quickly photograph the screen of, written Wi-Fi passwords on the fridge. The inspector does not take the laptop; they take the credential and use it later.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What does not typically get stolen</h2>

      <p>Large items, items that require force or noise to remove, items the inspector cannot leave with discreetly. The classic image of "burglar at an open home" is not what the data supports. Inspectors are not stealing televisions or carrying out laptops in a bag. The risk is small items that fit in a pocket and that the inspector can take while passing through a room briefly.</p>

      <p>This matters because it tells you where to focus preparation. You do not need to remove every valuable item from the home. You need to remove the small, portable, easily-pocketed items from the rooms where inspectors will be unsupervised even briefly.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The seller's preparation checklist before the first open home</h2>

      <p>Run this checklist before your first inspection. Once it is done, repeating it each weekend takes about ten minutes.</p>

      <p>Remove all jewellery from bedrooms and bathrooms. Store it in a safe that is bolted down, in a locked filing cabinet that does not look like a jewellery store, or off-site at a family member's home. Do not leave it in the bedside table or in a "hidden" location: those are the first places an opportunistic inspector looks.</p>

      <p>Remove cash from drawers and cupboards. Cash is the highest-frequency theft category because it is untraceable and small. If you typically keep some emergency cash in the home, take it with you for the duration of the campaign.</p>

      <p>Remove prescription medications from bathrooms. Store them in a locked cabinet, in a high cupboard the inspector will not check, or off-site. This is particularly important for opioids and benzodiazepines, which have street-resale value and are a known target.</p>

      <p>Remove sensitive mail, financial statements, and tax documents. These should not be visible anywhere a buyer will reasonably walk through. The kitchen bench, the entry table, and the study desk are the high-risk surfaces. Move them to a locked drawer or take them off-site.</p>

      <p>Lock home offices or remove sensitive documents from view. Buyers will sometimes open the door of a closed room out of curiosity. If the room is locked and the agent has a clear reason ready ("the owner uses this as a home office and asked for it to remain closed"), that is a normal and accepted setup.</p>

      <p>Unplug or hide spare keys: front door spares, car keys, safe keys. Inspectors who note the location of a spare key during an open home are setting up for a later return visit. Put all spare keys in one secure location off-site for the duration of the campaign.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What to leave visible</h2>

      <p>The aim is not to strip the home of personality. Buyers expect to see a lived-in home, and depersonalising too aggressively makes the property feel cold and harder to connect with. The right principle is "remove the items that signal high value and could be pocketed; leave the items that show this is a real home people live in."</p>

      <p>Everyday items: kitchenware, books on shelves, magazines on the coffee table, plants. These all stay.</p>

      <p>Personal photographs in moderation: a few framed photos communicate that the home is loved and lived in. Twenty framed photos of the family on every wall make it harder for buyers to imagine themselves in the space, but a few are fine and even helpful.</p>

      <p>Items that demonstrate the home's lifestyle: bicycles in the garage, surfboards in the carport, books on the shelves, a small library of cookbooks in the kitchen. These all communicate the home's character. They are not security risks because they are too large to pocket and too cumbersome to remove discreetly.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The agent's role in security</h2>

      <p>Experienced agents are the first line of physical security at an open home. The expectations to set with your agent are practical and reasonable.</p>

      <p>Two staff is the minimum for any active inspection. One agent at the entry signing visitors in, one agent positioned to monitor flow through the home. If your campaign is busy enough to attract twenty inspectors in a half-hour window, one staff member alone cannot maintain visual coverage.</p>

      <p>Each visitor signs in with name and contact. This is now standard practice across Brisbane and is enforced through agency policy. The sign-in serves two purposes: it gives the agent a way to follow up serious buyers, and it creates a record if anything goes missing during the inspection.</p>

      <p>Inspectors should not be allowed to wander into bedrooms or studies unaccompanied for more than a brief moment. Experienced agents move through the home in a way that maintains line of sight, particularly into the rooms where small items might be at risk. If you watch a busy open home, you will see the agent positioning themselves at the threshold of bedrooms while inspectors look in.</p>

      <p>Discuss the security setup with your agent before the first open home. A short conversation about which rooms will be locked, what to do about spare keys, and how the agent will manage flow at peak attendance is worth ten minutes and prevents most issues.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Open homes that need extra security</h2>

      <p>High-value properties (above $3m) often warrant a different setup. Private inspections by appointment with pre-qualified buyers, rather than general open homes, are common at this level. The buyer pool is narrower, the screening is tighter, and the property's contents are typically more valuable.</p>

      <p>Vacant properties are more vulnerable than occupied ones. There is no resident to detect signs of recent visits, and any items the seller has stored at the property are easier to access. If the home is vacant during the campaign, store everything of value off-site rather than relying on locked rooms within the property.</p>

      <p>Campaigns where many open homes are scheduled close together accumulate exposure. A four-week campaign with two open homes per week and a midweek inspection is two hundred or more individual inspectors through the home. The cumulative risk is not large in any single week, but the preparation routine needs to be consistent across every inspection.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What to do if something is missing</h2>

      <p>Do not panic. Search thoroughly first. Items are often misplaced rather than stolen, particularly small items that get moved during pre-inspection cleaning. Check the obvious places, then check the unusual ones.</p>

      <p>If you are confident the item is missing, report it to police promptly. Queensland Police take open-home thefts seriously, and a report on the same day or the day after is far more useful than one filed a week later.</p>

      <p>Request the agent's sign-in records. The agent should provide the sign-in sheet for the relevant inspection. If the agent is hesitant to share it, that is a separate issue that needs escalation.</p>

      <p>Review any visible CCTV footage from your home or from neighbours who have street-facing cameras. Cameras at neighbouring homes often capture the entry and exit of inspectors during the open home window.</p>

      <p>Notify your home insurance. Most policies cover theft during inspections, but you need to start the claim process while the evidence is fresh.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The insurance angle</h2>

      <p>Most home insurance policies cover theft during inspections, but typically only if reasonable security measures were taken. "Reasonable" is the load-bearing word here. If the policy is challenged, the question becomes whether you took the steps a reasonable seller would take: securing valuables, having an agent present, maintaining a visitor log.</p>

      <p>Documenting your pre-inspection preparation supports any claim. A photograph of valuables in the safe before the campaign, a record of the agent's inspection routine, the sign-in sheets from each open home: all of these strengthen a claim if something does go wrong. Most sellers will never need this documentation, but it takes a few minutes to set up and is straightforward to maintain.</p>

      <p>Review your policy's contents-cover limits before the campaign starts. Some policies have lower limits for jewellery or cash than for general contents, and an open-home theft of jewellery worth $30,000 might fall outside the policy if those limits were not adjusted. A short call to your insurer before the first open home is the right time to clarify.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The camera question</h2>

      <p>Discreet visible cameras are deterrents and are legal in common areas of your home. Cameras at the entry, in the living room, and in the kitchen are generally fine and are a reasonable security measure during a campaign. Buyers expect homes in the current era to have some level of camera coverage, particularly entry cameras.</p>

      <p>Do not record bathrooms or bedrooms. Covert recording in private areas is illegal in Queensland and elsewhere. The line between "common area" and "private area" is generally clear: bathrooms, bedrooms, and changing areas are private. Living rooms, kitchens, and entries are common.</p>

      <p>Audio recording of conversations may require both-party consent under Queensland law. The safe rule for an open home is video-only. Disable audio capture on your cameras for the duration of the campaign, and make sure any visible cameras have a small notice indicating that the area is under video surveillance. This both complies with the law and acts as a deterrent in itself.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The practical framework</h2>

      <p>A 30-minute pre-open-home checklist eliminates the vast majority of risk. Secure valuables, sensitive documents, and spare keys. Lock or close the rooms that should not be wandered into unaccompanied. Check that the agent has the sign-in sheet ready and a clear plan for the inspection flow.</p>

      <p>Trust the agent to manage the inspection but do not assume they will catch everything. Your preparation is the layer that matters most. A well-prepared home with no portable valuables visible is genuinely low-risk regardless of how many inspectors come through.</p>

      <p>Review your insurance position before the campaign starts. Make sure contents limits are appropriate, particularly for jewellery and cash. Document the preparation routine so any claim is straightforward to support if it ever needs to be made.</p>

      <p>And keep perspective. Open homes are the most efficient way to expose your property to a wide buyer pool, and the price benefit of running them well is large. The security risk is real but small and almost entirely manageable with basic preparation. Run the campaign with confidence.</p>

